accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCable television, on the brink of a boom in the 1970s, promised audiences a new media frontier-an expansive new variety of entertainment and information choices. Music video, 24-hour news, 24-hour weather, movie channels, children's channels, home shopping, and channels targeting groups based on demographic characteristics or interests were introduced.Cable Visions looks beyond broadcasting's mainstream, toward cable's alternatives, to critically consider the capacity of commercial media to serve the public interest. It offers an overview of the industry's history and regulatory trends, case studies of key cable newcomers aimed at niche markets (including Nickelodeon, BET, and HBO Latino), and analyses of programming forms introduced by cable TV (such as nature, cooking, sports, and history channels).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCable televisionzUnited States. 4aCable. 4aVisions. 4aalternatives. 4abeyond. 4abroadcastings. 4acables. 4acapacity. 4acommercial. 4aconsider. 4acritically. 4ainterest. 4alooks. 4amainstream. 4amedia. 4apublic. 4aserve. 4atoward. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBanet-Weiser, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChris, Cynthia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFreitas, Anthony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814739242.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MU